ofile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-13505/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-13505/canvas/1/56a1baf5-6e3a-402c-9338-08da6cc90944","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T19:24:01.321Z","creator":"lucia","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The composition of this scene echoes that of the previous one with Alma on the left and Reynolds on the right. The two small statues of bucking horses and people trying to get them under control that frame the newlyweds represent their force of will. In their relationship and in their marriage, Reynolds and Alma will be two wild horses who clash and contain immense energies. Similarly, the preceding poisoning may be read as Alma taming Reynolds the wild stallion.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-13505/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:31.94805194805202,124.67532467532466,374.02597402597405,213.50649350649354"}}}]}]}]}